came to shape the modern international order.The ideal river examines nineteenth-century efforts to establish international commissions on three transboundary rivers – the Rhine, the Danube, and the Congo. It charts how the Enlightenment ambition to tame the natural world, and human nature itself, became an international standard for rational and civilized authority and informed our geographical imagination of the international. This relationship of domination over nature shaped three core IR concepts central to the emergence of early international order: the territorial sovereign state; imperial hierarchies; and international organizations. The book contributes to environmental politics and international relations by highlighting how the relationship between society and nature is not a peripheral concern, but one at the heart of international politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational relationsxHistoryy19th century. 0aInternational rivers. 0aRiversxLaw and legislationxHistoryy19th century. 0aWater boundariesxHistoryy19th century. 4aPolitical Studies 2022. 7aLAW / Government / General.2bisacsh  aCongo.  aDanube.  aRhine.  aStandards of Civilization.  aenvironmental history.  aglobal governance.  ahierarchies.  aimperialism.  ainternational organisations.  asovereign state.1 aYao, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615439240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526154392423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526154392/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles